        The Buyer's Solicitor in a Queensland Property Sale: What Sellers Can Expect
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The buyer has their own solicitor. You have yours. Here's what the buyer's solicitor is actually doing during your sale, why they sometimes create delays, and what sellers should never do when the other side's lawyer gets in touch.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>In a Queensland property sale, the buyer will instruct their own solicitor to act on their behalf throughout the transaction. This is standard practice, and it reflects the complexity and financial significance of a property purchase. For sellers, the buyer's solicitor is a background presence who shapes the pace and sometimes the terms of the transaction. Understanding what that solicitor is doing, and where they can create friction, helps sellers stay calm when the process slows down in ways that feel inexplicable from the outside.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why the buyer has their own solicitor</h2>
      <p>A property purchase in Queensland involves a legally binding contract, a title that needs to be examined for encumbrances and restrictions, a finance process that requires coordination with a lender, and a settlement that involves the transfer of title and the movement of significant funds. The buyer's solicitor manages all of this on the buyer's behalf. Their duty is to the buyer, not to the transaction and certainly not to you as the seller.</p>

      <p>This is not an adversarial arrangement in most transactions. Both solicitors have an interest in a clean, straightforward settlement. But the buyer's solicitor will flag anything in the contract, the title, or the property's disclosure documents that represents a risk for their client. That is their job, and they would be falling short of their obligations if they did not do it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the buyer's solicitor does during the sale</h2>
      <p>After contracts are exchanged, the buyer's solicitor moves through a sequence of work. They review the contract thoroughly, including any special conditions that were negotiated during the offer process. They check that the contract accurately reflects what was agreed and that no terms are ambiguous or problematic for the buyer.</p>

      <p>They conduct title searches and due diligence enquiries. In Queensland, these include a search of the title to confirm ownership and check for registered encumbrances, caveats, and easements. They will also search for rates, land tax, and body corporate information if applicable. Any entry on the title that was not disclosed or that the buyer was not aware of will be flagged immediately.</p>

      <p>They manage the finance condition. Under the standard REIQ contract, the buyer has a finance period during which their finance approval must be obtained and confirmed. The buyer's solicitor coordinates with the buyer and their broker or lender to ensure the finance condition is either satisfied or a request for extension is made within the required timeframe. This is often where delays originate, as lender processing times are outside the solicitor's control.</p>

      <p>They coordinate settlement. As the settlement date approaches, the buyer's solicitor prepares the transfer documents, orders a final title search, liaises with the lender to arrange the settlement funds, and coordinates with your solicitor to agree on the settlement figures. In Queensland, settlements are now predominantly conducted electronically through PEXA, which has streamlined the process considerably but still requires precise coordination between both solicitors and the lender.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why the buyer's solicitor sometimes causes delays</h2>
      <p>Experienced sellers find the buyer's solicitor the most mystifying source of delays in the transaction, because the delays often seem to come without explanation. There are a few common causes.</p>

      <p>Requests for special conditions during the contract negotiation phase can slow or complicate the exchange of contracts. A buyer's solicitor who reviews the proposed contract and identifies concerns may advise their client to request additional conditions or modifications before signing. This is legitimate, but it can extend the time between offer acceptance and contract execution.</p>

      <p>Title queries arise when the buyer's solicitor finds something in the title searches that requires explanation. An easement that was not clearly disclosed, a historical caveat, or a restriction on the title that affects the buyer's plans can all trigger formal requisitions that your solicitor must respond to. Most are resolved straightforwardly, but the process takes time.</p>

      <p>Lender instructions are a frequent bottleneck. The buyer's solicitor can only proceed to settlement once they have received the lender's formal settlement instructions, which include the exact amount the lender is contributing and the conditions under which funds will be released. If the lender is slow to provide those instructions, the buyer's solicitor cannot set a settlement date, regardless of how organised everyone else is.</p>

      <p>Communication gaps between the buyer, their solicitor, their broker, and the lender can compound all of the above. When a buyer is managing their solicitor and their broker separately without a clear point of coordination, instructions can be delayed, documents go unreturned, and queries sit unanswered. This is not the solicitor's fault, but it creates delays that look, from the seller's side, like legal obstruction.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should not do when the buyer's solicitor contacts them</h2>
      <p>This is a point worth being direct about. If the buyer's solicitor contacts you directly, do not respond. Direct communication between a seller and the buyer's solicitor is almost always counterproductive and can create problems your own solicitor then needs to manage. The buyer's solicitor is not acting in your interests. Anything you say to them can be used in negotiations or in dispute resolution.</p>

      <p>Everything that needs to pass between the legal representatives should go through your solicitor. If you receive correspondence directly from the buyer's solicitor, forward it to your own solicitor and let them respond. This is the correct protocol, and a good solicitor will tell you the same thing. The same applies to your agent: your agent should not be providing legal information or making commitments to the buyer's solicitor on your behalf.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the two solicitors coordinate on settlement day</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, most settlements now take place through PEXA, the electronic conveyancing platform. On the day of settlement, both solicitors log in to the PEXA workspace, verify the settlement figures, confirm that all conditions have been satisfied, and authorise the lodgement and disbursement of funds. The title transfer and the payment of purchase funds happen simultaneously. When it works smoothly, settlement can be completed in minutes.</p>

      <p>Delays on settlement day most commonly arise from lender-side issues, where the lender's PEXA representative is slow to verify or authorise the transaction, or from last-minute queries on the settlement figures. Your solicitor and the buyer's solicitor will work to resolve these on the day. A delay of a few hours is not uncommon in a PEXA settlement, even when everything has been well-prepared, simply because there are multiple parties whose confirmation is required.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common buyer's solicitor requests that sellers find surprising</h2>
      <p>Sellers who have not sold recently are sometimes caught off guard by the requests that come through the buyer's solicitor. Requisitions on the title asking for statutory declarations about property improvements and council approvals are standard in Queensland and not a sign that something is wrong with your title. Pool compliance certificate requests, smoke alarm compliance confirmation, and requests for copies of any outstanding council notices are routine.</p>

      <p>A request for a settlement extension from the buyer's solicitor, citing lender processing times, is also common and should be considered on its merits. If the delay is genuine and a short extension resolves it without materially affecting your own plans, agreeing is usually the pragmatic approach. Your solicitor will advise you on whether the extension request is reasonable and whether any conditions should attach to your agreement.</p>

      <p>An experienced agent has navigated dozens of transactions where the buyer's solicitor has raised queries, requested extensions, or created delays that initially seemed concerning. In almost all cases, these are procedural matters that resolve without affecting the outcome of the sale. Having an agent who can translate what is happening and advise you on whether it warrants concern makes the process considerably less stressful.</p>

